  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Extract of letter handwritten and copied by unknown person. See Call No. Ms.A.1.1 v.7, p.35B for the original letter by William Lloyd Garrison to Alfred Harry Love, written on May 1, 1867. This passage is not identical to the original manuscript.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In this passage, William Lloyd Garrison discusses peace: &quot;The cause of peace and goodwill is dearer to me than the ruddy drops that run in my veins. Not that there can be peace before there is purity; not that there can be peace before there is the possession of impartial liberty and equal rights, ...&quot;</subfield>
